I can think of one way to write &quot;cd&quot; out-of-process from the shell: exec /bin/cd /some/path, which does chdir(&quot;/some/path&quot;) and execs your shell.  You&#x27;d lose your history and similar state, but if you had a shell that didn&#x27;t even put cd in-process, it probably doesn&#x27;t have history either.<p>Sample:<p><pre><code>    /tmp$ exec /tmp/cd /bin
    /bin$ exec /tmp/cd /home
    /home$ exec /tmp/cd /usr
    /usr$ 
</code></pre>
Sample code:<p><pre><code>    #include <err.h>
    #include <stdlib.h>
    #include <unistd.h>

    int main(int argc, char *argv[])
    {
        char *shell;
        if (argc != 2)
            errx(1, &quot;Usage: exec cd /some/path&quot;);
        if (chdir(argv[1]) == -1)
            err(1, &quot;chdir&quot;);
        shell = getenv(&quot;SHELL&quot;);
        if (!shell || !*shell)
            shell = &quot;/bin/sh&quot;;
        execl(shell, shell, NULL);
        err(1, &quot;exec&quot;);
    }</code></pre>
